Hurricane Safety and Preparedness

How Coastal Communities Prepare For Intensifying Hurricanes

By Ally Hirschlag

July 21, 2021

Before Hurricane Maria hit Puerto Rico in 2017, Zhureida del Valle didn’t do that much to prepare for hurricanes. Even though she’d seen a number of devastating hurricanes throughout her life there, she typically would only shop for supplies after a hurricane was imminent. They had lanterns and flashlights around since there were regular power outages in her area, but that was about it.

“I was prepared in case of an emergency with the bare minimum,” says de Valle.

That all changed after Hurricane Maria ripped through her hometown. De Valle and her husband and daughter left their apartment. which was wall-to-wall windows. and rode out the storm at a nearby hotel. They spent 10 hours in their room's bathroom, because the winds and driving rain were so terrifying.

After the storm had passed, they realized they didn't have potable water or enough food to stay there any longer. De Valle couldn’t call her family because all the cell phone towers were knocked out along with the power, so once her battery died, that was it. And since she didn’t have a battery-operated radio, she had no idea about the extent of the damage the hurricane had caused until much later.

“It took days for us to be able to even make a phone call, even longer to know what happened all over the Island,” says de Valle. “In fact, years [later], when someone reports the hurricane's effect on Puerto Rico, I always find myself watching footage that I never saw before because we were completely disconnected from the world.”

Three days later, they were able to check on their two properties. While their main residence had survived the storm, their second apartment, which they rent out, had been destroyed by winds and flooding.

The experience was harrowing and devastating, but it had one positive effect: de Valle is now always prepared for a major hurricane. Her family has boxes of batteries, at least eight battery-operated fans, a portable gas stove with supplemental gas tanks, and lots of non-perishable foods in a storage facility. She also purchased two back-up phones, one of which is a flip phone which she says is ideal to have in an emergency.

“Moving a SIM Card to a simple cell phone like those makes a charge last for days. The single most important thing that I learned during the long hours that María was blasting the Island was that communication was key to survival, and I needed something that would stay powered for a long time,” explains de Valle.

Finally, they moved to an apartment building with an electric generator so that if the grid goes offline, they will more than likely still have power. She even purchased a portable shower in case water has to be rationed, which happened during Maria.

A new game plan for more intense hurricane seasons

De Valle’s decision to supercharge her hurricane prep isn’t uncommon in coastal communities like San Juan, Puerto Rico. Hurricanes are getting stronger as a result of climate change. An NOAA and University of Wisconsin study found the chance of a hurricane being a category 3 or higher has gone up 8% each decade since 1979. Hurricanes also appear to be strengthening faster once they form, due to warming waters.

Many people in coastal communities seem to be recognizing this trend and enhancing their hurricane preparations accordingly. Whether they’ve been directly impacted by a major hurricane or seen how it’s impacted those close to them, they know that preparing for the worst is the best way to protect who and what you love from whatever lies ahead.

Advertisement

“María changed us for the better, I think,” says de Valle. “We learned that just winging it could end up costing lives or make trying to survive almost impossible; that it was better to have more items than you could need (you can then share with your neighbors), than trying to hunt for food and supplies.”

Home upgrades after a hurricane in South Florida

Jaclyn Strauss has lived through years of damage and loss due to hurricanes that have hit her hometown of South Florida. Three years ago after a hurricane barreled through the area, she was left without electricity for over a week. She also couldn’t get a hotel room within 300 miles of where she lived, so she had to stay in her home without air conditioning during a Florida summer with her two young children.

Since that whole ordeal, Strauss has upgraded her home in several ways. “I have added a whole-house generator to my home, ensured that all windows and doors are equipped with hurricane glass, and upgraded my garage door to hurricane grade,” says Strauss.

Donna Childs, a business owner in Rhode Island, also made home updates to her home inside and out. She added a serrated pipe around the front of her home that leads to the sewer line so heavy downpours won’t flood her property so much.

“The pipe and ground are covered with stones such that water flows over the stones, into the pipe and is brought away from the building, reducing the risk of water damage,” Childs explains. She also raised her home insurance policy coverage limits.

And just like de Valle, she’s increased her store of supplies because she anticipates a run on supplies and potential supply chain disruptions with the pandemic.

Hurricanes are getting more intense, and increased damage and devastation to coastal homes is likely over the coming hurricane seasons. But if coastal dwellers take steps to shore up their properties now, they may save themselves from expensive and potentially preventable losses in the future.
